# Strategy Onboarding

## Role Purpose
This is the master workflow that ties every other skill together. A new signal idea is worthless — and potentially dangerous — without passing through each gate systematically. This skill defines the complete onboarding process, who owns each step, and the hard criteria that must be met before a strategy touches real capital.

## Onboarding Phases Overview
```
Phase 1: Research & Specification     (QR owns)
Phase 2: Data Validation              (DS/DE owns)
Phase 3: Backtesting                  (QR + QA own)
Phase 4: Walk-Forward Validation      (QR + Walk-Forward Optimizer)
Phase 5: Implementation               (QD owns)
Phase 6: Unit & Integration Testing   (QA owns)
Phase 7: Paper Trading                (QA + QT own)
Phase 8: Micro Live Deployment        (QT + Risk Quant own)
Phase 9: Scale-Up                     (PM + Treasury own)
```

---

## Phase 1: Research & Specification
**Owner: Quantitative Researcher**
**Exit Criteria: Completed signal spec document**

```
[ ] Hypothesis written in plain English (one sentence)
[ ] Market inefficiency clearly identified
[ ] Expected win rate and hold duration estimated
[ ] Data requirements fully listed (exact field names, frequency, source)
[ ] Signal formula defined with all parameters named and typed
[ ] Entry conditions written as unambiguous boolean logic
[ ] Exit conditions defined in priority order
[ ] ATR regime fit specified (LOW / MEDIUM / HIGH)
[ ] Conflict behavior defined (what blocks this signal)
[ ] Edge cases documented (thin book, news spike, post-halt, etc.)
[ ] Signal spec document delivered to QD and DS/DE
```

---

## Phase 2: Data Validation
**Owner: Data Scientist / Engineer**
**Exit Criteria: Clean dataset with validation report**

```
[ ] All required data fields confirmed available
[ ] Data completeness checked: % of expected timestamps present
[ ] Gaps identified and documented
[ ] Data validated against schema (no negative prices, no zero volumes, etc.)
[ ] Cross-source validation complete (Binance vs Coinbase prices aligned)
[ ] Timestamp normalization confirmed (all UTC, all to 15-min boundaries)
[ ] Survivorship bias assessed (are we missing delisted contracts?)
[ ] Minimum dataset size confirmed: >= 2000 labeled examples
[ ] Validation report delivered to QR
```

---

## Phase 3: Backtesting
**Owner: Quantitative Researcher + QA/Simulation Engineer**
**Exit Criteria: Backtest clears all minimum thresholds**

```
[ ] Backtest implemented with NO look-ahead bias (verified manually)
[ ] Realistic fill assumptions applied (slippage, partial fills, fees)
[ ] Kalshi fee structure modeled correctly (see cost-fee-optimizer)
[ ] Backtest run on full dataset with 70/30 train/test split
[ ] Test set not touched during any optimization

Minimum thresholds (ALL must be met on test set):
[ ] Win rate > 52%
[ ] Sharpe ratio > 1.0
[ ] Max drawdown < 20%
[ ] Total trades > 200
[ ] Profit factor > 1.2
[ ] Fee-adjusted net Sharpe > 0.8

Red flags that kill the backtest (ANY fails it):
[ ] Sharpe > 3.0 (likely overfitting)
[ ] Win rate > 70% (too good to be true)
[ ] < 200 trades (insufficient sample)
[ ] Performance concentrated in < 3 months of data
[ ] Backtest report delivered
```

---

## Phase 4: Walk-Forward Validation
**Owner: Quantitative Researcher**
**Exit Criteria: Edge confirmed across multiple independent windows**

```
[ ] Walk-forward windows configured (see walk-forward-optimizer)
[ ] Parameters optimized on rolling train windows only
[ ] Each test window is genuinely unseen data
[ ] Results analyzed across all windows

Minimum acceptance:
[ ] > 60% of test windows show positive Sharpe (> 0.5)
[ ] Average test Sharpe > 0.8 across all windows
[ ] Overfitting gap (train - test Sharpe) < 1.0 on average
[ ] Final parameters selected by majority vote, NOT by best single window
[ ] Walk-forward report delivered to QD and Strats
```

---

## Phase 5: Implementation
**Owner: Quant Developer**
**Exit Criteria: Code matches signal spec exactly, all tests written**

```
[ ] Signal implemented exactly as specified — no undocumented deviations
[ ] All parameters loaded from config (not hardcoded)
[ ] Type hints on all public functions
[ ] Exception handling on all API calls and signal evaluations
[ ] Logging before and after every trade action (see logging-observability)
[ ] Heartbeat written on each loop iteration
[ ] Signal passed through SignalConflictResolver (never submitted directly)
[ ] Contract selection logic integrated (see contract-selection)
[ ] Rate limiter wrapped around all order calls (see risk-manager-compliance-officer)
[ ] Unit tests written for:
    [ ] Signal calculation with known inputs → expected outputs
    [ ] Edge cases (thin book, zero volume, extreme values)
    [ ] Entry blocked in wrong ATR regime
    [ ] Exit conditions trigger correctly
[ ] Code review complete
[ ] QD signs off: "Implementation matches spec"
```

---

## Phase 6: Integration Testing
**Owner: QA / Simulation Engineer**
**Exit Criteria: All regression tests pass, fill model calibrated**

```
[ ] Full regression test suite passes (100% — no skips)
[ ] Integration test: signal → coordinator → order manager → fill (end-to-end)
[ ] Mock Kalshi API used for all order submission tests
[ ] Paper fill model validated against recent real Kalshi fill data
[ ] Latency measured: signal evaluation < 50ms, order submission P99 < 500ms
[ ] No memory leaks confirmed (run for 24h on dev, monitor RSS)
[ ] Bot gracefully handles:
    [ ] WebSocket disconnect mid-evaluation
    [ ] DB connection failure
    [ ] Order rejection (all codes)
    [ ] Contract expiry with open position
    [ ] SIGTERM with open position (close before shutdown)
[ ] QA sign-off: "Code is testable and tested"
```

---

## Phase 7: Paper Trading
**Owner: QA/Simulation Engineer + Quantitative Trader**
**Exit Criteria: Paper results within acceptable range of backtest**

```
Minimum paper trading duration: 4 weeks OR 100 trades (whichever is later)

[ ] Paper bot deployed to paper environment (separate from production)
[ ] Live Kalshi data used (not historical replay)
[ ] Realistic fill model active
[ ] All alerts configured in slack_only mode
[ ] QT reviewing paper results weekly

Acceptance criteria:
[ ] Paper win rate within ±5pp of backtest
[ ] Paper Sharpe > 0.8
[ ] Paper fill rate > 75%
[ ] No critical bugs observed
[ ] Backtest-vs-live gap analysis complete (see qa-simulation-engineer)
[ ] QT sign-off: "Paper results acceptable for live deployment"
[ ] Risk Quant sign-off: "Risk parameters confirmed"
```

---

## Phase 8: Micro Live Deployment
**Owner: Quantitative Trader + Risk Quant**
**Exit Criteria: Live performance confirms edge at minimum size**

```
Deployment configuration:
  - Position sizing: 10% of normal (minimum viable)
  - Duration: 4 weeks minimum OR 100 live trades
  - Circuit breakers: fully active
  - Alerts: fully active (including SMS/pager)

[ ] Deploy during low-volatility window (avoid US open, major news)
[ ] QT monitoring first 48 hours closely
[ ] Performance tracked weekly against paper and backtest baselines

Graduation criteria (to scale up):
[ ] Live win rate > 50% (allows for small live vs paper degradation)
[ ] Live Sharpe > 0.8 (3-week rolling)
[ ] No unexpected behavior or anomalous trades
[ ] Fill rate > 70%
[ ] Risk Quant confirms: drawdown and exposure within limits
[ ] PM + QT sign-off to scale up
```

---

## Phase 9: Scale-Up
**Owner: Portfolio Manager + Treasury**
**Exit Criteria: Strategy fully integrated into portfolio**

```
[ ] Scale from micro (10%) → small (25%) → standard (50%) per deployment-stages
[ ] Each stage requires minimum 4 weeks at current stage before scaling
[ ] Performance attribution run monthly
[ ] Signal health monitored (IC, win rate decay checks)
[ ] Strategy added to portfolio-manager-quant monthly review
[ ] Treasury confirms capital allocation is within structure limits
[ ] If ETH market expansion being considered, see multi-market-expansion
```

